<dl id="n54146j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54146j">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54146j"> 146(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> men<font color="green">[his her]</font> staff / ivystains = sweat <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54146j"><li>FW 25.015 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n54146j">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n54146j">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54146j">MS BL 47476b-474</ms> </li><li>JJA 50:278 <a name="ad8" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#ad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad8.htm#n54146j">Draft: I.1&sect;1.8</a>/2.8</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Chez les Herero, &laquo;ondume, <mark>la canne h&eacute;r&eacute;ditaire du p&egrave;re</mark>, dont il se servait de son vivant, est conserv&eacute;e apr&egrave;s sa mort, et repr&eacute;sente l&apos;anc&ecirc;tre en certaines circonstances ; aussi lui fait-on des offrandes de viande et de lait.&raquo; On pourrait, il est vrai, regarder ici la canne du mort comme une de ses appartenances, puisque <mark>sa main l&apos;a impr&eacute;gn&eacute;e de sa sueur</mark>. <br><font color="green">[Among the Herero, "ondume, the father&apos;s cane, which he used during his lifetime, is preserved after his death, and represents the ancestor in certain circumstances; so they offer him meat and milk. One could, it is true, look here at the dead man&apos;s cane as one of his belongings, since his hand permeated it with his sweat.]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 214</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
